 permit isolated incidents to\ndistract interest from the main theme.\nThe down stumbles in the sawdust, and\nwe laugh; the riding girl falls and breaks\nan arm, bnt the circus goes on.\n*We need not lose faith in representative\ngovernment because of the oil scandal,\nand the Veterans' Bureau scandal. The\nmalefactors and those who operated prof\nitably in the twilight sone between right\nand wrong, will be punished. That is\ncertain. And better men will take their\nplaces.\nEven a protracted and devastating world\nwar, followed by the economic calamities\nof 1920 and 1921, have not halted the\nmarch of progress in the United States. In\ni'- dustry and commerce have again stripped\n-for a great effort. 1\nfe But a little while ago influenza swept\nthrough the nation, killing around a half\nmillion people, leaving bitter sorrow in its\nwake. But the disaster had no effect\nupon the destiny of the nation.\nJapan still groans from the ghastly\nwound taflioted by earthquakes, but Japan\nIs by no means done., It is only tempo\nrarily crippled and Inoouvenleaoed.\nBcoancc men and women are socially\nholder they demand and obtain divorces\nin such numbers aa to distress and alarm\nJudicious observers. Tet but *a fraction\nof marriages end in divorce. Most mar\nriages are successful, bnt of these we have\nno occasion to hear anything interesting,\nexcept the daily announcement of the\nbirths of new babiee\u2014and a correspond\ning i&rease in the birth rate of new hopes\nand new, fresh young dreams.\nRead your incident frorii a background\nbroad as earth and as old as man.\nTHE AID OF THE CHURCH.\nCommissioner Estfl of the Salvation\nArmy, has declared that the consensus\nof opinion gathered from social workers\nfrom twenty States holds that no person\naddicted to the use of drugs has ever been\ncompletely cured of his disease without a\nreligious experience. The moral stimulus\nrequired for this supreme effort of the\nwill can be supplied only by a fervent re\nligious experience.\n'Whereupon several metropolitan news\npapers have risen to appeal to the church\nto devote themselves to this work which\nthey alone can do. This unsolicited advice\nIndicates a narrow view of the functions\nof organized Christianity. The scope of\nthe work of the church is far broader and\nof more importance than their operations\nas cures for drug addicts. That the church\nis more effective than medicine in ef\nfecting the cure of drug addicts grows out\nof its message to weak and suffering hu\nmanity. And the church would indeed have\na narrow field if it had drug addicts as its\nonly subjects of inspiration. Christianity\nhelps drug addicts only because it uplifts\nand helps every other class of afflicted and\nsuffering humanity. It is the same power\nthat gives heart and courage to the lowly,\nand downcast that offers hope to the un\nfortunate drug addict.\nThe statement by Commissioner Estil Is\nmuch more significant than any comments\nUpon it by metropolitan newspapers, which\nare constantly looking for short cuts to\nevery goal. It would be both comforta\nble and unjust to turn over the job of\ncuring drug addicts to th\u00ab churcl# but it\nIs only a part and a small part of the work\nof the church. Many doctors, who have\nbeen engaged in the work of treating ad\ndicts to alcohol and to other drugs ^iave\ndeclared that the man saturated in and\naccustomed to the use of alcohol can be\ncured, but the cure is surest and best pro\nmoted by some moral kick. On the other\nband they declare that no confirmed drug\naddict, no person who acquires the disease\nattributed to drug addiction can be safely\nregarded as cured, after taking treatment.\nWhen men whose lives have been given to\nStruggles with the drug addicts say that\nthere is one and only one certain means of\neffecting a cure and that is with the aid\n\u2022f1 a stirring religious experience by the\npatient, they have said something of pro\nfound importance.\nPROSPECTS: NIL.\nColonel Musgrove is in command of the\nChemical Warfare Division in Alabama.\nSlogan: \u201cFrightfulnese.\u201d Object: To set\ntip a snake doctor soviet in America.\nMIL MUSCROVE\u2019S SILENCE ABOUT\nHIMSELF AND HIS FLANS. j\nThe editor of the Ontonta Democrat,\nwho incidentally is president of tho Ala\nbama Press Association, has been reading\nthe Mangrove Campaign literature In\nsearch of a line commendatory to the\nstatesmanship snd political merits of Ly\ncurgus Breckenridge Musgrove. And bare\nis Editor ^Stephens\u2019s report:\nWe have been carefully reading all the\nliterature sent ont by the Musgrove\nCampaign Committee and we have tailed\nto find a single line In any of this vast\namount of printed matted to commend\nCol. Musgrove to the people of Alabama\nas a suitable man for the Presidency.\n*Thls literature Is a vilification and a\nmisrepresentation of Senator Underwood\nand nls views on various public ques\ntions.\nIt doss not tell you that Mr. Musgrove\nIs a statesman or that he hag any Ideas\nabout governmental affairs or the great\nproblems now facing the government.\nIt Is not an appeal to you to oast an*\nIntelligent ballet, but It Is an appeal to\ntho voter to let prejudice eonttol his ac\ntions.\nThey have dug Into Senator Under\nwood's record for the past thirty years\nand have failed to show a single In\nstance where his actions have been In\nfluenced by corruption or anything but\npure motives. They have sifted It from\none end to the other. They have tried to\nplace him In a false light before the\nvoters but they have utterly failed in\nproducing the proof.\nWhdre Is there found another man In\npublic life with a record like thatT\nWe are not appealing to you to vote\nfor Mr. Underwood but we do appeal to\nyou to use reason and common sense and\ncast' an Intelligent ballot. The election\ncomes next Tuesday. Oo to the polls\nand oast the ballot of an Intelligent\nman or woman.\nair. musgrove snouia not oe cmaea iur\nfailure to commend himself adequately.\nAs Presidential candidate there is noth\ning in the world to commend Mr. ne\ngroes, If we except the circumstance that\nhe was born in the United States. And\nMr. Muagrove\u2019s sense of humor would not\npermit him to make bogus claims in fur\ntherance of his candidacy for President.\nHence he does not claim to be a Presiden\ntial candidate. Presumably he would not\neven permit his name to be put before the'\nNational convention if by any comic mira\ncle' ,he should win, and name the delega\ntion. He would turn his delegates over\nto somebody else immediately upon arrival\nin New York. Who would get them, no\nbody knows, but presumably Bryan would\nget them.\nMr. Musgrove has never, said that he\nwould actually stand for the nomination\nhimself, and he has never sa}d whom he\nwould support for the nomination. Yet he\nhas the assurance to ask Alabsma Demo\ncrats to sign and seal their proxy and de\nliver it to a man who does not even say\nwhom\u2019he favors for President! \u201cFriends,\nyou must trust me to find somebody to\nvote for, but you must not embarrass pie\nby inquiring after my intentions,*' Mr.\nMusgrove says by his actions.\nMr. Musgrovs's \"candidacy** is as ab\nsurd as the candidacy of Lucy Page Gas\nton in 1920, when she asked for the Pres\nidency on an anti-cigarette platform.\nABOLISHING THE CALIPHATE.\nOn March Srd, the national assembly of\nthe government of Turkey, located at An\ngora, formally abolished the Caliphate and\nordered the expulsion of the Caliph from\nTurkey. At two o\u2019clock the next morn\ning a delegation from the National Assem\nbly ordered the Caliph to mount his throne\nand read to him the decree which abolished\nthe Caliphate and ordered him and all\nhis relatives into exile.\nA few hours later the Caliph left Con\nstantinople for Switzerland, with only two\nwives to his name. With one stroke of\nfate he had lost six palaces, all fully\nstaffed with servants and eight hundred\nand odd wives. The Caliph was the spir\nitual head of Mohammedans the world\nover. This high religious position held in\nawe by Mussulman was an ex-officio hon\nor of the Sultan of Turkey. But when the\nSultanate was abolished, it s^med foolish\nto retain the Caliphate. But when the\nTurkish politicians told the Caliph that he\nwas fired they had to get him out of Tur\nkey, where he would have been a trouble\nbreeder, because there were many Mo*\nhammedans who regarded him with ven\neration and who did not believe that the\nsun would rise and set regularly unless\na Caliph was supervising the job.\nProbably no people are so alarmed at\nthe radicalism of their government than\nare\\he people of Turkey at the acts of\nthe national government, which seems de\ntermined to westernize Turkey. When the\nyoung Turks staged their successful revo\nlution, they held back from touching the\nCaliphate. They deposed the Sultan but\npermitted him to remain Caliph as his\npresence was regarded as a (ftstinct asset\nto Turkey in its international affairs. To\nbe the spiritual head of many million faith\nful followers of the Prophet gave the hold\ner a vast and not entirely artificial power.\nSo when Mustapha Kemal, the Turkish\nmilitary hero who defeated the Greeks,\nabolished the Sultanate and sent Moham\nmed VI into exile they held back from\nabolishing the Caliphate in fear that it\nwould arouse the animosities of the Mos\nlem world. This was in 1922 and they\nmade Mohammed\u2019s cousin, Abdul Caliph\nand invested him with the robe of the\nProphet.\nUnder the older Sultans the Caliphate\nwas considered their most valuable prerog\native. As the head of Islam they depend\ned upon their position as Caliph to in\nsure their support of the Mohammedans of\nthe world.\nThe title of Caliph was assumed by Se\nlim in the Sixteenth Century, when he ob\ntained the relics of the Prophets, his stan\ndard and his mantle from the last of the\nAbbadises.\nMohammedan scholars have always ques\ntioned the right of Selim to the title of\nCaliph. They contended that it was based\nupon conquest and purchase and that Se\nlim failed in having the necessary quali\nfications for the office, in that he was not\na member of the tribe of Koreish, to which\nMohammed belonged. Selim overcame\nthis last obstacle by officially proclaiming\nhimself a member of the Koreish. In spite\nof scholastic opposition the Moslem world\naccepted Selim and his successors as Sultan\nas the Caliph, principally because Turkey\nwmi the most important Mohammedan\ncountry.\nBat this division of sentiment sad be\nlief existed all through the years. Every\nnow and then sons leaders and teachers\namong the scholars weald rise and as\nsault the false Caliph. Perhaps this his\ntoric division emboldened the National\nAssembly to put through its resolution of\nabolition.\nIn other years the Sultans frequently\nemployed their power as Caliphs in con\ntroversies with Christian powers having\na large Mussulman population. The Ca\nliphs as the Spiritual leaders of the Moham\nmedans could always and frequently did\ngain their point by threatening to call a\njahad and raise the standard in a, holy\nwar. This was a favorite diplomatic de\nvice of Abdul Hamid when he was hard\npressed by Great Britain, Russia or France.\nHe threatened to call a jahad or holy war,\nto which all the faithful must respond.\nBut this old cry of \u201cWolf\u201d failed during\nthe World War. Mohammed V declared\na holy war when Turkey decided to enter\nthe World War on the side of Germany,\nbut Islam refused to respond to the call\nto arms. Instead many Moslems in India\njoined the British army and fought against\nTurkey and the Arabs fought for their\nown independence against Turkey. The\nattitude of the Angora government evi\ndently is that the Caliphate has lost its\npower in international politics and that a\njahad or holy war would be of litle avail\nin the Moslem world of today.\nBat it Is altogether likely that a new\nCaliph will rise in some other Mohamme\ndan country, Egypt, Morocco, or Arabia,\nand we can expect several European coun\ntries that are not Mohammedan to take\nan active part in selecting a Caliph that\nwill be \u201cright\u201d on international ques\ntions. Twenty years ago the question of\nthe new Caliphate would have been a\ngrave international issue. But the World\nWar brought about many changes. Rus\nsia and France today are not near so much\ninterested in the personality of the new\nCaliph as they would have been twenty\nyears ago. Great Britain is the country\nat present more vitally interested in the\nthought and action of the Moslems of the\nworld than any modern nation. Great Bri\ntain has today 70,000,000 Mohammedan\nsubjects. Her experience in India' has\ntaught her that the Caliphate can cause\nher much trouble. The British government\nhas however, announced that it would\nhave no part in the selection of a new\nCaliphate.\nThe policy of the British Empire as it\nhas been semi-officially snnounced is that\nthe selection of a Caliph is a matter for\nthe Mohammedans themselves to decide as\nhis place of residence. Islam has expressed\nno choice as to the selection' of a Caliph\nbut it is the consensus of opinion that his\nplace of residence should be at Mecca, the\ncenter of the Moslem world. This might\nbe taken to mean that Hussein, ruler of\nHuifey, will add the title of Caliph to that\nof King. It is a mere coincidence that\nGreat Britain exercises a sort of suserainty\nover Hessoin and his country.\nTHE RECOVERY OF ARMOUR.\nIn 1928 Armour and Company, packers,\nearned a profit of $15,600,000 as against\na loss of $7,600,000 the year before. More\nsignificant still is the fact that Armour\nand Company paid $53,000,000 of its bank\nloans. Thus a great industrial firm gets\nout of the woods in rather short order. It\nwas not so many months ago that Ogden\nArmour was in serious financial difficul\nties, due to the agricultural depression in\nthn West, and his eomnanv\norganization.\nThe Chicago correspondent of the Phila\ndelphia Public Ledger and the New York\nEvening Post, says the report of .^rmour\nfor 1923 is of \u201cunusual import.\u201d \"It\nmeans something more than good fortune\nfor an army of stockholders. It signifies\nthe recovery of a great industry' that\nwas rescued by a banking syndicate not\nmany months ago from a position that was\nmore of a menace than the public was ever\ntold.\u201d\nIn the last six months of comparative\nprosperity Armour has contributed \u201cma\nterially to the return of prosperity to ag\nriculture, and agriculture in this part of\nthe country is certainly moving toward\nprosperity. Packers, mail order houses,\nfarm implement makers and automobile\nbuilders all are projecting into the fu\nture plans that express complete confi\ndence in the farm future.\u201d\nNICOTINE.\nA Paris husband said to his young wife:\n\"It is ridiculous to use snuff at your age.\nWhy not leave that to old people?\u201d She\nsaid to the police afterwards: \"He made\nme mad, and so I shot him unconsciously.\u201d\nThere was a time in the world when peo\nple engaged in no acrimonious discussion\nof the snuff-dipping habit, since nearly\neverybody either sniffed or dipped it That\ncelebrated Italian resident of France, Na\npoleon Bonaparte, sniffed it. We believe\nalso, that the late lamented General\nGeorge Washington was a snuff addict\nLater, men chewed and smoked more,\nand only women used snuff. Now there are\nthree classes of women, snuff-users, ci\ngarette smokers and total abstainers. We\ncannot as yet forecast the outcome of the\nstruggle for mastery between the three\ngroups.\nTHE WALL STREET OFF-SET.\nThe Democratic convention will be held\nin the greatest Democratic stronghold\nnorth of Mason %nd Dixon\u2019s line. The\nrest of the country may go crazy every\nnow and then, but New York City almost\nalways goes Democratic.\nTammany isn\u2019t popular in the sense\nthat the Apostle Paul is popular, but in\nnational elections it\u2019s a comfort to know\nthat Tammany is on guard with its gas\nhouse veterans.\nHOW IT STARTED.\n\"At any rate, Mr*. Murphy, no on* can \u00bbay\nI'm two-faced.\"\n\"Faith, no, Mr*. Jones. Sur*. an' If y*r\nwere, you\u2019d l*av* that 'un at 'ome.\"_Mel\nbourne 1\u2019unoh.\nThe Passing Throng\n_ bt Amour* nun.\nT\u00bb\u00abf H\u00abHt Bridges la\nThcss Dim Aak Ssinggs\nSteal may ft* more enduring than wood.\nAnd then aiala ateel may not be more en\nduring than wood. It all depends npoa\nwhere the ateel la placed, how It la pro\ntected and what kind of ateel It la. And\nthen again the wood would depend upon the\nkind of wood, how K waa protected, etc.\nBut this Is a tale of wood. It was brought\nto Montgomery Thursday by Hubert 8cruggs\nBirmingham member of the State Highway\nCommlaelon.\nMr. Scruggs has Just finished an Inspec\ntion of the oonstruotlon of the new bridge\nthat la to span the Chattabooohee river at\nEufaula. One end of this bridge will be In\nAlabama and the other end In Georgia.\nThe new bridge will take the place of the\nold wooden covered bridge now spanning\nthe Chattahoochee at that point.\n\u201cI saw wood In the old bridge,\u201d said Mr.\nScrdggs. \"that oould be nsed In construc\ntion now and outlast five times new lumber.\nThe pine which went Into the old bridge\nwas cut from long leaf yellow pine before\nthe pine had been turpentined. Th< old\nbridge was built, I understand. In the year\n1SS2. Timbers In this old bridge have now\nbeen In use 72 years and they are in a\nremarkable state of preservation. I heard\nIn Eufaula the old bridge was built by\nslave labor. Tes, they certainly built\nbridges In those days.\"\n.Municipal OmnaMp Great\nBarden Says Oklahoma Paper.\nThe McAlester News-Capital la not a great\nbeliever In municipal ownership. Aa witness\na recent editorial:\n\"Public ownerahlp of publlo utilities and\noperation of the same' without profit Js a\nbeautiful dream, but few people stop to\nthink what It might mean. .-The cltlsens\nhave their hands full now managing financ\ning, taxing themselves and ralslhg money\nto handle all that Is expected of them un\nder present condltlona They must pave\nstreets, build sewers, maintain parka, clean\nstreets, conduct publlo schools; employ po\nlice and fire departments, and support hos\npitals and Jalla Add to this the manage\nment of street railroads, telephone systems,\ngas plants, electric lighting, childrens' play\ngrounds. municipal dance halls, publlo au\nditoriums, golf links and numerous other\nthings proposed, and you double the tax\npayer's burdens.\"\n\"The payrolls and financing of all public\nutility enterprises wopld exhaust the cred\nit and taxing power of municipalities. Is\nnot the pret.nt system of using both pri\nvate and public credit, private and publlo\nenterprise under sound public regulation a\nbetter system and does It not lead to a\nmaximum of community development! If\nIt were all loaded upon' the general tax\npayer, would It not be a staggering burden\nand destroy enterprise and initiative!\"\n\nGood Heavens! Stoeklnglesa\nLadles! Shame ea Underwood.\nCampaigns may come and campaigns may\ngo. but never another like the Alabama Pres\nidential campaign. That great sane, conser\nvative, Jeffersonian leader. Senator Oscar W.\nUnderwood of Alabama, has a plank In his\nplatform to take the stockings off the la\ndles, the shoes, to, and make them go\nbarefooted. So say the speakers and \u2018\u2018whis\nperers\u2019\u2019 swarming over the State for Colonel\nI* Breckenrldge Musgrove of Jasper.\nColonel Musgrove Is against stocklngletfc\nladles and shoeless ladies. This Is the in\nference which Underwood men draw from\nthe alegation of his speakers and \u201cwhis\nperers'*. Ergo, ladies votes for Musgrove\nand retain your right to wear stockings and\nshoes. A vote for Musgrove Is an endorse\nment of shoes and stockings for ladles. A\nvote for Underwood means shoeless and\nstooklngless ladles. Rises there no defen\nder for ooreetless ladles! Is there none who\nwill enter the lists for them.\nAnd again, a speaker, and a preacher at\nthat, (I hope he was not a Baptist) rose up\nin Coffee oounty last week and made the\ncharge that Senator Underwood's trip to\nEurope last summer was for the purpose of\nmaking a deal with the Pope of Rome\nwhereby the Senator was to get $6,000,000\nfor delivering the Alabama delegation to\nthe next convention to whomsoever the\nPope would name. Just think of It $6,000,\n000 fow\u2019the Alabama delegation alone! What\nwill a majority of all delegates be worth!\nAnd how much coin has the Pope to spend\nIn the Democratic campaign, anyway! And\nyet these are but two of the latest campaign\nIssues.\nSenator Underwood la\nFine Spirit*\u2014Melton.\nOakley W. Melton Is a world war veteran\nof Elmore county. He Is also Secretary to\nSenator Oscar W. Underwood and In addi\ntion to that Is a member of the Alabama\nLegislature from Elmore county, coming\ndown to the lower House. Mr. Melton Is In\nMontgomery. He came to Alabama last week\nand he reports that Senator Underwood Is In\nthe best of health and spirits. He says the\nSenator-Is very confident of the Democratic\nnomination for President. He says the\nSenator is not only confident of being nomi\nnated but of being elected after being nomi\nnated.\n\"Senator Underwood never looked better\nthan at the present time\" said Mr. Melton.\n\"He Is In fine health and spirits. He Is re\nceiving so many encouraging offers of sup\nfort In his race for the Democratic nomina\ntion that he Is naturally optimistic. He be\nlieves he Is going to be nominated and my\npersonal knowledge of the general situa\ntion over the country leads me to believe\nthat he Is right In believing he Is to be\nnondlnated. You have no Idea how poplar\nSenator Underwood Is all over the coun\ntry.\u201d\nMr. Melton says Washington Is all stirred\nup over the Teapot Dome and there Is a\ngeneral prophesy of Democratic success In\n1924 with the proper man nominated for the\nPresidency. \"The taint of oil is on Wash\nington,\" said Mr. Melton. 'You hear oil\neverywhere. With an \u2018oil-lease* candidate I\ncan see nothing but Democratto success.\u201d\nMr. Melton will remain In Alabama until\nafter the election next Tuesday. He will\nvote in bis box In Elmore county.\n\nJoe* Ore** of Dallas\nCounty Over for a Day.\nJoe Green of Dallas county was In Mont\ngomery Thursday. Mr. Green Is a former\nmember of several Alabama Legislatures.\nHe Is a locomotive engineer and the man\nwho has been engaging In litigation with\nthe order of engineers. Mr. Green was one\nof the leaders In each Legislature of which\nhe was a member. He Is a sane Democrat.\nHe has been a consistent advocate for pro\nhibition and was one of the leading fight\ner* for the cause at two sessions of the\nLegislature.\nMr. Green Is looking fine and fat. \"I\nam getting a little too stout.\" said Mr.\nGreen Thursday. \"Guess X will have to diet\na little or do something In the way of hand\nsprings and somesaults.\"\nMr. Green was one member of the Legis\nlatures In which he served who oould fight\nfor a thing and still keep on good terms\nwith the enemy. When the days of fighting\nwere over, Mr. Green always forgot his ad\nversaries and was willing to mingle with\nthem as friend*. He had no hard words for\nthose who differed with him on matters of\npolicy or of principle. He got to be known\nas \"Harmonlser\" Green because of his uncan\nny ability to get things straightened out\nafter It looked as If they wer, hopelessly\ntangled.\n\"We are going to roll up a nice vote for\nSenator Underwood In Dallae next Tuesday,\"\nsaid Mr. Green.\nCOMPLETE ARRANGEMENTS,\n\u201cCrlmeor^ Gulch hasn't parking space\nenough to accomodate the automobiles that\ncome to town.\"\n\"No elr.\" answered Cactus Joe, \"thi* here\nle a growing oommunlty with expenses to\nmeet. If w* can't ketch a flivver for speed\n!n' we get It fur standln\u2019 etlU.\"\u2014Washington\nStar.\nHIS. BUT NOT HERS.\nThe old colored Janitor's employer aeked\nhim Why he was sporting around In his\nSunduv clothes when It wasn't a holiday.\n\"Well, you see. boss,\" he replied, \"I'm cel\nebratin\u2019 iny golden wedding.\"\n\"But isn't your wife celebrating tt with\nyouf\n\"Oh, Mandy! She ain't got nothin' to do\nwith It. She\u2019* Jae' my third wife.\"\u2014Boston\nTranscript.\nLetters to Editor\nunoxvi vrmmom.\nMiter The Advertlaer:\nTour linotype men did a tip-top Job as\nvenal, on my article which appeared in\nyour leane of thla date, but some ene\ndropped a elug before It not to tbe forma,\nand tbna marred the quotation fi'om Gorer\nnor Hammond\u2019a apeech of withdrawal from\nthe United Statea Senate, at tbe time of ee\neeealon. Like almoat all the Confederate\nleadera, Hammond oppoaed aeceaalon aa a\npolicy, but had Ions advocated It aa a right\nunder the conatltntlon, In order to avoid\nit aa a poas/ble fact. Hla worda have a\napeelal algnlflcance at the preaent moment,\nand eoupd like a propheay of the preaent\n'Republican break-down. I give the entire\nPaaaage again:\nSenator Seward had Jaat eatd that the\neeepter of political power had now panned\nfrom the South, and Hammond replied: \"Sir,\nwhat the Senator aaya la true. The power\nhaa paaaed from our handa to youra. But do\nnot forget It\u2014it cannot be forgotten. It la\nwritten on the brlghteat page of hlatory\u2014>\nthat we, the alaveholdera of the South, took\nour country In her Infancy, and, after ruling\nher for nearly alxty out of the aeventy\nyeara of her exlatence, we return her to yon\nwithout a apot upon her honor, matehleaa In\nher aplendor. Incalculable In her power, the\npride and admiration of the world. Time\nwill ahow what you will do with her, but\nno time can dim our glory, or dlmlnlah your\nreaponalhlllty.\u201d C. R. LAMAR.\n42( Finley Ave., Montgomery, Ala.\nUnderwood and Ford\nIf the people will oonslder the present can\ndidacy of Senator Underwood In the light of\nthe record, assertions of interested little pol\niticians who are trying to tear down and\ndamage the South's greatest statesman will\nfade Into Insignificance. Take, for Instance,\nthe oharge being made by some of these paid\ndefamers that \"Underwood Is favorable to\nthe railroads,\" and they point to his vote for\nthe Esch-Cummlns bill.\nThey forget that there had to ba a bridge\nto cross from the war-time extravagances\nand lunacy of management, back to private\nownership, and that this bill guaranteed em\nployment at good wages to thousands of\nrailroad menl\nWithout a guarantee of earnings for a\ntime, what would have happened? Wages\nwould have been cut to far below the pre\nwar figures, for there was a deficit of a\nbillion nine hundred million to face. Some\nof the so-called \"leaders\" of labor never\nseem to get It Into their heads that unless\nthe railroads prosper railway labor cannot\nprosper? So, by his vote, Underwood guar\nanteed employment at fair' wages\u2014and for\nthis Is being assailed by self-constituted\nspokesmen who have never been affirma\ntively for anybody or anything In their Uvea\nbut always \"agin.\"\nSenator Underwood has, ever slnoe he wae\nIn public life, been an ardent advocate of\nwaterway development. He backed Sena\ntor Bankhead when he was In the House\non the Warrior and other river Improvement\n\u2014the Improvement of the Mississippi and\nother streams that railroads did not wish to\nsee navigation upon again. Does that look\nas though he was 'for the railroads,*' as some\nof the parrot-Uke assertions charge?\nThen again: On February 1922, when It\nlooked as though the Ford offer was going\nto be referred to the Military Affairs Com\nmittee of the Senate, an unfriendly commit\ntee which would have made an adverse re\nport, Senator Underwood made a speech\nwhich was so convincing and so thoroughly\nshamed the conspirators who were prepar\ning to lynch the Ford offer In private, that\nhis motion prevailed, and the offer was re\nferred to the Agricultural Committee, whloh\nwas friendly. Underwood saved the Ford of\nfer right then and there from an adverse re\nport.\nHe Is the main reliance of the Ford advo\ncates, and he la the one who will make the\nreal fight for the Ford offer In the Senate.\nIf those who are Interested In Ford, Inter\nested In this great development coming to\nAlabama. Interested In cheap fertiliser for\nthe farmers, will Just refleot for a minute\nthey can see what effect a lessened vote In\nAlabama would mean.\nIt would be used In Washington by the\nenemies of the Ford offer as Indication that\nAlabama Is not wholeheartedly for It. and\nhad failed to give Senator Underwood a vote\nof confidence on his stand for the Ford offer.\nEvery friend of the Ford offer should put\nall small' differences of opinion aside\u2014If\nany exist; and see that every Ford advocate\nrallies to Senator Underwood and tell the\nworld that Alabama Is still standing In -the\nfaith and still for the Ford offer. For, In\nthe coming battle In the Senate hardly three\nweeks off, a failure to give Underwood this\nvote of confidence will probably mean such\na weakening of the morale of the Ford ad\nvocates as that the proposition will be beat\nen. A strong vote of confidence In Ford\nand Underwood, as the chief spokesman,\nwill mean victory; will hearten Senator Un\nderwood to the fray and encourage him to\ndo his best for an appreciative constituency\n\u2014Birmingham News.\nWhat Is a Journalist?\nTh\u00bb Investigation In Washington has turn\ned the people of the entire country under the\nlimelight. In every profession, in every\nwork, we find so many faithless. We see\nrascality In places where we thought there\nwould be sanctity. We see those who boast\nof the highest patriotism making it a screen\nfor their greed.\nThese things are either the aftermath of\nthe war or they have been going on and\nthe war simply brought them In sight.\nThe newspaper profession has some horri\nble examples. Schaffer, Bonfils and McLean\nare unpleasant exhibits. Eaoh one of them\nIs In trouble because he was not truly\nan editor or a publisher. McLean inherited\nhis papers. He hasn't enough natural ability\nto write ten consecutive lines. He ran\nthem through others. It must be said for\nthe others that they kept them fairly\nstraight. But McLean used them to forward\nhis social fortune in Washington and Ohio.\nHe was the w hlte-haired boy during the\nHarding administration. Before Harding was\nInaugurated McLean gave him great social\nattention. It was pleasing both to Harding\nand his wife. In their domestic lives they\nwere both good honest souls and the warm\nlights of social distinction which the Mo\nLean\u2019s effued around them made them com\nfortable.\nMcLcad is IntftrcstAd In strict railways\nand other utilities. He has no business own\ning: papers unless he runs them himself\nSchaffer was probably the most disheart\nening of the bunch. He had a veneer of ed\nucation and culture. His business was chief\nly in grain dealing. The first paper he sot i\nhold of he used for uplifting. He was strong\non the uplift. He was a purist In politics.\nHe bought a lot of other papers. The more\nhe bought the more sanctified he seemed to 1\nhave become. Lo and behold, we find that\nhe got his out of oil. He made a miserable j\nshowing before the Senate committee. Long\nago we saw the halo of sanctity over his I\nhead. Now we see that his feet are clay i\nand resting In oil cans.\nBonfils never pretended to be much. Bon- j\nfils always flew a flag upon which was In- j\nscribed \u201ccaveat emptor,\" Bonfils was in all\nsorts of business.\nNow men In all sorts of business are some- j\ntimes tempted to use the prestige of their\n^newspaper ownership to forward their busi\nness In other enterprises.\nBonfils. Schaffer and MoLean ought to\ngive up their newspapers, McLean has j\nenough money to atract a sufficient number j\nof lackeys and hangers-on to make life in- j\nteresting. Schaffer freed of his newspaper\ncould give more attention to his grain and\nother business. Bonfils out of his paper\nwould find his circuses, mining operations\nand other things which he has his hands\nin all sufficient to absorb his time.\nThese men may be \u201cfairly\" honest\u2014just\nas honest as the average in their viewpolnte.\n,But not being trained In Journalism, not\nhaving a pride In their profession, not being\nable to master and practice the intellectual\nmechanics of It they are likely to become\ncolor blind when they must decide on the\nright thing and advocate that thing to the\nend.\nBut the bok in not closed. A few lawyers\nhave fallen to- the wayside. Tbre* or\nDr. Frank Crane i\n<ml mn crams'm mKh*\n\u00ablT\u00ably In lUfauM\u2014In Iki IntKMir\nAirntta* u4 n* Umtagtu Inn. Af\ntletes IIMIIM under hla-is nay .An\nAlabama mnmtn an Rfrlat \u2014Hn tram\nU mn *M. Mnt at Dr. Onart am\n\u2022*f* la ether\u2019 papers have\nalnaO at the tlaaa at thetr erlgtaal\nnlaaaa raara age. (My Tha AlrarOnr aa4\nTha Ram are prlattag tha faeah. pratlaaa\naapakllaha4 artlelaa ft Dp. Crane.)\na a a\nWOODROW WILtOI\nWoodrow Wllaon' haa passed Into history.\nHa haa laft tha (laid of ooatonttoa and\nstepped into hla place before tha Jury at thi\ncenturies.\nOar astlmata of ovary man daring hla Ufa\nla vitiated by the reactions of hla parson\nallty. T\nOur enthusiastic affection for him any an.\nalt him more than ho deserves; onr Intense\naversion to him may load ns to 'do t*l-e In\njustice.\nDeath a ponses away onr llkao sad\nlikes and leaves the figure standing tree.\nWoodrow Wilson will rank as one of the\nthree great Presidents of the United States\nwith Abraham Lincoln and George Washing\nton.\nBach of these men Is groat, as ho repre\nsented and embodied a great national Idea.\nWashington stood for the Integrity of\nAmerican Independence.\nLincoln stood for the Indlseotable nntty of\nthe oountry and for the abolition of human\nWoodrow Wilson will forever be Identified\nwith America's organio union with the\nother nations of the world.\nHe represents a distinct phass of the\nworld's progress; the first step In the aban\ndonment of the old order of rival nations\nand the beginning of the new order of co\noperative nations. He will be forever Iden\ntified with the ldea*of the supremacy of the\narbitrament of law as a substitute for the\nold arbitrament of war.\nHe It was who seised and alung to the one\nworth-while thing that was the result of the\ngreatest war of all time; the union of all\nthe nations of the earth to substitute law\nfor arms.\nThere are. and have been, but two Ideas\nof world government; one the Idea of em\npire. the other the Idea of federation.\nEmpire means that the world Is to be\nkept In order by one nation making Itself\nsupreme over all the others. It has been\ntried over and over again and Invariably has\nfailed.\nRome tried It. Spain tried It Napoleon\ntried It. Germany tried It It broke down\nevery time.\nAt the close of the great war, largely\nthrough the efforts of Woodrow Wilson, the\nworld started upon the program of federa\ntion.\nLike every other forward movement la\nhuman progress, this Idea was assailed with\nridicule, anger and the outory that It was\noontrary to human nature. It was denounoed\nJust as the constitution of the United States\nwas denounoed and as the abolition of hu\nman slavery was denounced.\n'To this Idea of world federation. Wood\nrow Wilson gave his life utterly.\nAs he recedes Into the perspective of years\nhis figure will loom larger and more ma\njestic. For the size of a man In history\ndoes not depend upon the Incidents of his\npersonality. It depends upon the magnitude\nof the star to which he hitches his wagon.\nWhen the names of those grlse and pru\ndent ones, who mocked this Joseph and hts\ndreams, who sneered at the greatest plan\never conceived for the redemption of hu\nmanity from war, and who broke the spirit\nand crushed the body of Its chief protago\nnist, shall have gone to the portion of weeds\nand forgoUen faces, the fame of Woodrow\nWllsoiff whose clean mind saw the logic\nof destiny and whose strong heart darod to'\nfollow shall bloom, ever green, in the gar\nden of the world's memory.\nHis was\n\u201cThe divine\nInsanity of noble minds;\nThat never falters nor abates.\nBut \u2019abort and endures and wafts.\u201c\nCopyright. 19*4. by the Wneeler Newspaper\nSyndicate.\nToday 25 Years Ago\n(From The Advertiser .Files, March T, 18M.)\nMr. Mortimer Meyer was receiving congra\ntulations of his friends yesterday on hts bril\nliant achievement winning the honors In\noratorical contest, by which he was selected\nto represent Montgomery at the District\nGrand Lodge debate to be held in Memphis\nIn May.\n\nMaster Clinton Hunter, eldest child and\nonly son of Mr. and Mrs. Larry W. Hunter,\ndied at his parents' residence. No. 28 Amanda\nstreet, at o'clock yesterday morning.\na\nMrs. W. A. Davis of Anniston, passed thru\nthe city yesterday on the way to Eufaula\nto attend the funeral of Mrs. B. B. Davis.\nFarming Big Business\nFarmer* frequently ansart that their la\nthe biggest business in the world. Some\ntimes they are believed. They tell the truth,\nnevertheless. Without going Into figures to\ntell of the great volum* of farm production\nIt Is In order, even for the Jjiformatlon of\nsome farmers themselves to give a few fig\nures with reference to the enormous amount\nof business that Is being done by farm or\nganizations, co-operatively, that Is. Th*\nfigures that are presented have been com\nplied by the United States Department of\nAgriculture, and show that more than two\nbillion dollars of business was done by farm\ners' organizations In the year 1023. This\nestimate Is based on the reports from 6,639\nfarmer organizations which did a bus\niness that aggregated $1,200,000,000 In\ntwelve months.\nAbout 2.000 organizations delayed their\nreports, which, when received and tabulated\nwill add to the totals thus far reported.\nAbout 90 per cent of th* 8.IIS organisations\nreporting were engaged, primarily. In sell\ning farm products, those In the grain mar\nketing class leading with about SO per cent\nso engaged; dairy product* 22 per cent;\nlivestock 14 per cant; fruits and vegetables\n11 per cent. The summary of th* report\ngoes more Into detail as follows;\nTwo thousand six hundred grain organi\nzations did a total business estimated at\n$490,000,000; 1,841 dairy products organiza\ntions a total business of $300,000,000; 1,182\nlivestock shipping associations a business\nof $220,000,000. and 966 fruit and vegetable\nassociations a total business of $280,000,000.\nSeventy-eight cotton co-operativse did $100,\n000.000, and 14 tobacco organizations $132,\n000.000.\nMany persons have an Idea that although\nthe farmers of th* United States are being\nurged constantly to do cooperative market\ning that they ar* not doing very much of\nIt. The above-quoted figures must convince\norttlc* that they are In error, that th* farm\ners ar* co-operating, that they ar* market\ning more scientifically than ever before.\nNevertheless, th* fact remains that coopera\ntive marketing Is not being done as exten\nsively. and as beneficially as It should be.\nRut th* business Is comp ratlvely new;\nfarmers are beginning only to learn how\nto do It properly and efficiently. As they\ngain experience so will they gain In co-oper\native marketing, Increase In the aggregate\nvolume of business done.\nConsidering that oo-operattv* marketing\nIs comparatively new. In practice, and that\nIt Is not being employed extensively as It\nwill be In a few more year*, there Is abun\ndant reason to congratulate th* farmers who\nar* marketing oo-operativaly. on the splen\ndid showing they ar* abl* to make.\nBig as is the farming business It will b*\nmade bigger and better as wall, with the\nemployment of more praettoal methods, par\nticularly In the matter of marketing, pro\nduction being pretty well In hand. Co-op\neration is winning Ita way, and the co-opera\ntive farmers, it appears, sre in the pre\nferred class.\u2014Jacksonville Tlmes-Unlon.\neditors of th# thousands In the oountry have\ncheapened th* profeselon. but there are oth\ners In all the other lines of human endeavor\nwho grs deflecting the moral average line\nof our citizenship In the direction of the\ne*v\u00ab not n t-UM\u2014hU OanaMnUJ","height":"28148","width":"19624"}}
